 2ï¸âƒ£ JavaScript Data Types

 ğŸ”¹ Primitive Data Types

| Type      | Example         |
|  |  |
| Number    | `10`, `3.5`     |
| String    | `"Hello"`       |
| Boolean   | `true`, `false` |
| Undefined | `let x;`        |
| Null      | `let y = null`  |
| BigInt    | `123n`          |
| Symbol    | `Symbol("id")`  |

js
typeof 10        // "number"
typeof "Hi"      // "string"
typeof null      // "object" (JS bug)




 ğŸ”¹ Non-Primitive (Reference) Types

| Type     | Example         |
| -- |  |
| Object   | `{name:"Uday"}` |
| Array    | `[1,2,3]`       |
| Function | `function() {}` |



 3ï¸âƒ£ JavaScript Functions

A function is a block of reusable code.

 ğŸ”¹ Normal Function

js
function add(a, b) {
  return a + b
}


 ğŸ”¹ Function Expression

js
const add = function(a, b) {
  return a + b
}


 ğŸ”¹ Arrow Function

js
const add = (a, b) => a + b


 ğŸ”¹ Callback Function

js
function greet(name, callback) {
  callback(name)
}

greet("Uday", function(n) {
  console.log("Hello", n)
})




 4ï¸âƒ£ JavaScript Arrays

Arrays store multiple values in a single variable.

js
let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Orange"]


 ğŸ”¹ Array Index

js
fruits[0]   // "Apple"




 5ï¸âƒ£ Important Array Functions

 ğŸ”¹ forEach()

â¡ Executes a function for each element
â¡ Does NOT return a new array

js
let nums = [1, 2, 3]

nums.forEach(num => {
  console.log(num * 2)
})




 ğŸ”¹ map()

â¡ Transforms array
â¡ Returns new array

js
let nums = [1, 2, 3]

let doubled = nums.map(num => num * 2)
// [2, 4, 6]




 ğŸ”¹ filter()

â¡ Filters values based on condition
â¡ Returns new array

js
let nums = [10, 20, 30, 40]

let result = nums.filter(n => n > 20)
// [30, 40]




 ğŸ”¹ reduce()

â¡ Reduces array to a single value

js
let nums = [1, 2, 3, 4]

let sum = nums.reduce((total, num) => {
  return total + num
}, 0)

// sum = 10


ğŸ”¹ Real Example:

js
let prices = [100, 200, 300]

let total = prices.reduce((acc, price) => acc + price, 0)




 6ï¸âƒ£ DOM (Document Object Model)

